14. Pythia: in the most ancient times Delphi, a chief seat of the worship of Apollo, was called Pytho, Apollo the Pythius, and his priestesS, the Pythia. She uttered the oracles while seated upon a tripod or three-legged stool; but as the sounds she made were unintelligible to questioners, they were taken down by priests of the temple, and in the form of hexameter verse communicated to inquirers.
